Analyze the following PlantUML use case model and detect if it contains any antipatterns.
Base your analysis solely on the model provided. Do not use any outside knowledge.


PlantUML Model:
@startuml
' Version 1 – contains Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

actor "Registrar" as Registrar
actor "Teacher" as Teacher
actor "Principal" as Principal

rectangle "School Administration System" {
  usecase "Manage Class Schedule" as UC1
  usecase "Enroll Student" as UC2
  usecase "Validate Student Documents" as UC3
  usecase "Record Grades" as UC4
  usecase "Generate Report Card" as UC5
}

Registrar -- UC1
Registrar -- UC2
UC2 ..> UC3 : <<include>>
Teacher -- UC4
Principal -- UC5

@enduml


Answer:
Antipattern Detected: Functional Decomposition: Using the include relationship

   Constructs Involved: Enroll Student (UC2), Validate Student Documents (UC3), the <<include>> relationship from UC2 to UC3
   Explanation: "Validate Student Documents" (UC3) is an inclusion use case that is included by only one use case ("Enroll Student", UC2). UC3 is not associated with any actor directly — no actor interacts with it. UC3 does not include, extend, generalize, or specialize any other use case, nor is it extended by any other use case. It represents an internal procedural step of enrollment (document validation) rather than a complete, independently meaningful service yielding an observable result to an actor. This is classic functional decomposition: the enrollment service has been artificially broken into sub-steps via <<include>>, where the inclusion use case serves no standalone purpose.
